WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.751 --> 00:00:02.377
♪♪

00:00:02.377 --> 00:00:04.504
KELLY: Memory
is a powerful thing.

00:00:04.504 --> 00:00:07.299
♪♪

00:00:07.299 --> 00:00:09.760
There are some events
that stick in the mind...

00:00:09.760 --> 00:00:11.887
♪♪

00:00:11.887 --> 00:00:13.430
...forever defining

00:00:13.430 --> 00:00:17.351
the difference
between before and after,

00:00:17.351 --> 00:00:20.938
and instantly redefining
everything that matters.

00:00:20.938 --> 00:00:23.690
For the soldiers and families

00:00:23.690 --> 00:00:27.027
of the Army's
1st Cavalry Division,

00:00:27.027 --> 00:00:31.365
memories of April 4, 2004,
still loom large.

00:00:32.908 --> 00:00:34.201
AGUERO: Where the hell
is everyone?

00:00:34.201 --> 00:00:37.120
♪♪

00:00:37.120 --> 00:00:38.372
CHEN: Ambush!

00:00:38.372 --> 00:00:43.293
(clock ticking)

00:00:43.293 --> 00:00:45.963
KELLY: Stories summed up
in a single date

00:00:45.963 --> 00:00:49.675
that has come to be known
simply as Black Sunday.

00:00:49.675 --> 00:00:52.135
WILD: You make memories
on days like April 4th

00:00:52.135 --> 00:00:55.639
that you never forget about,
no matter how much you want to.

00:00:55.639 --> 00:00:58.100
KELLY: Reconciling
these memories

00:00:58.100 --> 00:01:00.310
can be the work of a lifetime.

00:01:00.310 --> 00:01:03.730
Simply revisiting them
takes an uncommon bravery.

00:01:03.730 --> 00:01:05.899
GUZMAN: Everybody was scared.
I mean, we're all human.

00:01:05.899 --> 00:01:07.317
I thought
I was gonna die that day.

00:01:07.317 --> 00:01:09.945
♪♪

00:01:09.945 --> 00:01:11.196
KELLY: Re-creating
these moments

00:01:11.196 --> 00:01:12.990
is work of another kind...

00:01:12.990 --> 00:01:14.700
SALOMON: Action!

00:01:14.700 --> 00:01:16.868
KELLY: ...requiring
an equally uncommon passion.

00:01:16.868 --> 00:01:18.620
ALANNE: I took the
responsibility very seriously

00:01:18.620 --> 00:01:20.038
that this was a true story,

00:01:20.038 --> 00:01:22.291
and we're dealing
with real-life people.

00:01:22.291 --> 00:01:26.795
BEAVERS: I am humbled
to be a part of this.

00:01:26.795 --> 00:01:28.422
I feel so much privilege.

00:01:28.422 --> 00:01:31.717
BOSWORTH: I feel very honored
to tell this story.

00:01:31.717 --> 00:01:34.011
KELLY: 13 years
after Black Sunday,

00:01:34.011 --> 00:01:37.222
National Geographic and
a dedicated team of filmmakers

00:01:37.222 --> 00:01:38.598
are bringing
these events to life...

00:01:38.598 --> 00:01:40.600
SALOMON: And Action!

00:01:40.600 --> 00:01:42.394
KELLY: Working hand-in-hand
with the soldiers

00:01:42.394 --> 00:01:44.730
and families who were there
to tell their stories,

00:01:44.730 --> 00:01:47.357
and honor the memory
of those who were lost.

00:01:47.357 --> 00:01:50.444
I owe it to them
to do this the best that I can,

00:01:50.444 --> 00:01:52.863
because the country should know.

00:01:52.863 --> 00:01:55.490
This is "First Look:
The Long Road Home."

00:01:55.490 --> 00:01:57.784
RIDDELL: Sir?
AGUERO: Punch us through!

00:01:57.784 --> 00:01:58.994
RIDDELL: Aah!

00:01:58.994 --> 00:02:09.004
♪♪

00:02:09.004 --> 00:02:12.591
♪♪

00:02:12.591 --> 00:02:16.470
ALANNE: April 4, 2004,
was the fourth day in Iraq

00:02:16.470 --> 00:02:19.014
for a 1st Calvary Division
platoon.

00:02:19.014 --> 00:02:21.141
So, 19 men were out
on sanitation duty.

00:02:21.141 --> 00:02:23.060
JACKSON: How is this
warriors' work?

00:02:23.060 --> 00:02:25.062
ALANNE: None of these men
had ever been in combat before.

00:02:25.062 --> 00:02:27.105
HAYHURST: Welcome
to Sadr City, Jackson.

00:02:27.105 --> 00:02:28.940
RADDATZ: They thought
they were going

00:02:28.940 --> 00:02:30.609
to keep the peace over there.

00:02:30.609 --> 00:02:32.277
SPICER: We wanted to work
with the people

00:02:32.277 --> 00:02:33.862
and do something positive,

00:02:33.862 --> 00:02:36.365
and not just roll in there
like an occupation force.

00:02:36.365 --> 00:02:38.075
VOLESKY: Let's
try to keep the peace.

00:02:38.075 --> 00:02:39.993
Red One, return to base.
Over.

00:02:39.993 --> 00:02:41.578
AGUERO: Roger that, Lancer Six.

00:02:41.578 --> 00:02:43.330
ALANNE: And then, just as
they're about to head back

00:02:43.330 --> 00:02:44.998
to their
forward operating base...

00:02:44.998 --> 00:02:47.417
AGUERO: Listen. Was that...
(machine-gun fire)

00:02:47.417 --> 00:02:49.628
ALANNE: ...they were ambushed.
(machine-gun fire)

00:02:49.628 --> 00:02:50.921
BOURQUIN: Watch that glide!
Stop the vehicle!

00:02:50.921 --> 00:02:52.005
(tires screech)

00:02:52.005 --> 00:02:54.299
Comanche Red, this is Red Four!

00:02:54.299 --> 00:02:56.051
We have contact!
SLEVIN: Within minutes,

00:02:56.051 --> 00:02:59.137
we came under fire
from essentially all directions.

00:02:59.137 --> 00:03:00.722
(indistinct shouting)

00:03:00.722 --> 00:03:02.307
ALANNE: Two of their vehicles
became disabled...

00:03:02.307 --> 00:03:04.226
BOURQUIN: We got to get the hell
off of this street.

00:03:04.226 --> 00:03:06.228
ALANNE: ...so they had to
seek shelter in the city,

00:03:06.228 --> 00:03:09.731
and became trapped with a family
in the middle of this maze,

00:03:09.731 --> 00:03:11.691
and no one had any idea
where they were.

00:03:11.691 --> 00:03:13.610
LUPITA: We just heard
something happened in Sadr City.

00:03:13.610 --> 00:03:15.529
LeAnn: It's just
a peacekeeping mission.

00:03:15.529 --> 00:03:17.364
They'll be fine.
ALANNE: So now

00:03:17.364 --> 00:03:19.449
equally newly-arrived men
who didn't know the city

00:03:19.449 --> 00:03:21.576
had to go in,
in unarmored Humvees

00:03:21.576 --> 00:03:23.370
and open trucks
to get their brothers.

00:03:23.370 --> 00:03:24.788
ARSIAGA: We'll be sitting ducks.

00:03:24.788 --> 00:03:27.541
BEAVERS: A litany of
rescue attempts went out

00:03:27.541 --> 00:03:30.335
to try to get to where
these guys were pinned down.

00:03:30.335 --> 00:03:31.878
RANDAZZO: Stay alert.

00:03:31.878 --> 00:03:33.630
Lancer Six and Rescue Two
are inbound.

00:03:33.630 --> 00:03:34.965
SPICER: Three more blocks
to Delta, sir.

00:03:34.965 --> 00:03:36.466
WEIBLEY: Burning debris ahead!

00:03:36.466 --> 00:03:38.802
RITTER: On the way there,
roads are blocked off

00:03:38.802 --> 00:03:41.471
and they're shooting
at them from all angles.

00:03:41.471 --> 00:03:44.057
ALANNE: It was an
extraordinarily brave

00:03:44.057 --> 00:03:46.143
and costly rescue mission.

00:03:46.143 --> 00:03:49.354
AGUERRO: We're almost totally
black on ammo!

00:03:49.354 --> 00:03:51.898
BOSWORTH: It knocked the wind
out of everyone --

00:03:51.898 --> 00:03:54.025
soldiers there in Iraq,

00:03:54.025 --> 00:03:55.652
and then also everyone at home.

00:03:55.652 --> 00:03:58.822
HARDIE: Belinda?
BELINDA: What's the matter?

00:03:58.822 --> 00:04:01.491
HARDIE: CNN just said there was
an ambush in Baghdad.

00:04:01.491 --> 00:04:03.243
Four soldiers dead.
BELINDA: What?

00:04:03.243 --> 00:04:05.328
PAXTON: I think you're always,
somewhere deep down,

00:04:05.328 --> 00:04:07.914
waiting for that call
and hoping that it never comes.

00:04:07.914 --> 00:04:10.792
ROY: No one's contacted you?
AMBER: No.

00:04:10.792 --> 00:04:12.210
ROY: There's been an attack
in Iraq.

00:04:12.210 --> 00:04:13.962
CALLIES: The person
who fights overseas

00:04:13.962 --> 00:04:16.506
isn't the only one at war.
The whole family goes to war.

00:04:16.506 --> 00:04:17.841
AMBER: Roy, what's happening?

00:04:17.841 --> 00:04:20.343
ROY: Platoon was ambushed
in Sadr City.

00:04:20.343 --> 00:04:23.346
4 dead, at least 40 wounded.

00:04:23.346 --> 00:04:27.184
♪♪

00:04:27.184 --> 00:04:31.396
ALANNE: We are all very mindful
of our solemn responsibility

00:04:31.396 --> 00:04:33.064
in telling this story,

00:04:33.064 --> 00:04:36.067
and we are especially
mindful today, on April 4th,

00:04:36.067 --> 00:04:40.322
which this year marks the 13th
anniversary of Black Sunday

00:04:40.322 --> 00:04:44.910
and the battles in Sadr City
that we are retelling the world.

00:04:44.910 --> 00:04:47.287
WOMAN: I'm so tiny.
BOSWORTH: (laughs)

00:04:47.287 --> 00:04:48.955
BEAVERS: It's an amazing road
to get here.

00:04:48.955 --> 00:04:50.624
SOLDIER: Thanks, man.
BEAVERS: Thanks so much, man.

00:04:50.624 --> 00:04:52.417
SPICER: Today has been
more than I could've imagined,

00:04:52.417 --> 00:04:54.419
from the moment that we got
together this morning,

00:04:54.419 --> 00:04:55.921
with the crew and the cast,

00:04:55.921 --> 00:04:57.672
and our guys did
the moment of silence.

00:04:57.672 --> 00:04:59.966
I thought that that was
a perfect way to start the day.

00:04:59.966 --> 00:05:02.427
RADDATZ: I'd like to read
the names of the fallen.

00:05:02.427 --> 00:05:04.971
We will observe
a moment of silence

00:05:04.971 --> 00:05:09.059
at the beginning of the whistle,
and a whistle will mark the end.

00:05:09.059 --> 00:05:10.894
Thank you all.

00:05:10.894 --> 00:05:13.313
BOURQUIN: It was very emotional.

00:05:13.313 --> 00:05:16.274
I remember crying numerous times
on complete strangers.

00:05:16.274 --> 00:05:19.986
But it was a bonding moment,
just to be actually here

00:05:19.986 --> 00:05:21.404
with Gold Star family members.

00:05:21.404 --> 00:05:23.573
And the people
whose children died

00:05:23.573 --> 00:05:25.158
coming up to try to save me,

00:05:25.158 --> 00:05:27.118
really put a new
perspective on things,

00:05:27.118 --> 00:05:29.496
because it's been something I've
been avoiding for a long time.

00:05:29.496 --> 00:05:31.790
It's, you know, how do you
walk up to somebody and say,

00:05:31.790 --> 00:05:35.001
"Hey, you know, I'm alive
because your son died."

00:05:35.001 --> 00:05:37.045
You know, and then show them
pictures of your kids.

00:05:37.045 --> 00:05:40.423
It was a rough day,
but I'm glad it happened,

00:05:40.423 --> 00:05:42.592
because a lot of healing
for me individually

00:05:42.592 --> 00:05:44.511
just happened that day, even
though it took a lot of time,

00:05:44.511 --> 00:05:45.637
but it was a good experience.

00:05:45.637 --> 00:05:47.305
You see the black flags?

00:05:47.305 --> 00:05:49.182
I didn't even realize
they just had those until now.

00:05:49.182 --> 00:05:51.351
They must've just put those up.
It looks spot-on, doesn't it?

00:05:51.351 --> 00:05:53.979
A lot of other veterans
are able to go back

00:05:53.979 --> 00:05:56.314
to their battlefields,
whereas we won't.

00:05:56.314 --> 00:05:58.608
I don't think we'll do it
anytime in this lifetime.

00:05:58.608 --> 00:06:00.652
AGUERO: This little thing
on the wall over here gets me,

00:06:00.652 --> 00:06:02.195
because I remember that spot.

00:06:02.195 --> 00:06:03.989
And they did a pretty good
job of reproducing it --

00:06:03.989 --> 00:06:05.699
the writing over here
on the side.

00:06:05.699 --> 00:06:07.325
BOURQUIN: Now we get this
opportunity, while we're young,

00:06:07.325 --> 00:06:09.661
to still be able to go through
and see it, feel it,

00:06:09.661 --> 00:06:12.122
touch it, kick the dirt,
let it sting our eyes.

00:06:12.122 --> 00:06:14.291
The only thing that's not here
is the smell right now.

00:06:14.291 --> 00:06:15.875
ALANNE: It's been an incredibly
massive operation

00:06:15.875 --> 00:06:17.460
here in Fort Hood.

00:06:17.460 --> 00:06:20.130
BOURQUIN: These are
the two houses, right here.

00:06:20.130 --> 00:06:24.467
RADDATZ: The scope of this set
is just incredible.

00:06:24.467 --> 00:06:29.055
REED: We're standing at the end
of an 800-foot-long road,

00:06:29.055 --> 00:06:33.184
so we've constructed
1,500 feet worth of Sadr City

00:06:33.184 --> 00:06:35.312
in various interpretations.

00:06:35.312 --> 00:06:36.938
ALANNE: There's over
a hundred buildings

00:06:36.938 --> 00:06:39.441
that we have constructed
to re-create Sadr City.

00:06:39.441 --> 00:06:41.151
This is more than
three football fields long.

00:06:41.151 --> 00:06:44.404
It is the largest set
working in North America today.

00:06:44.404 --> 00:06:48.033
REED: I have a photograph of you
standing right here.

00:06:48.033 --> 00:06:50.160
The photograph is you like this.

00:06:50.160 --> 00:06:53.288
You took your helmet off,

00:06:53.288 --> 00:06:55.999
and you got in a lot of trouble
for taking your helmet off.

00:06:55.999 --> 00:06:59.336
SPICER: Martha Raddatz is
the news correspondent

00:06:59.336 --> 00:07:01.087
that had spent time with us
over in Iraq.

00:07:01.087 --> 00:07:03.465
She really saw the experience
that we had had

00:07:03.465 --> 00:07:06.509
was something significant,
and she just kept coming back

00:07:06.509 --> 00:07:08.053
throughout our year
that we were there.

00:07:08.053 --> 00:07:09.846
RADDATZ: When I was writing
the book,

00:07:09.846 --> 00:07:13.933
I never imagined that someday
I would see this re-created.

00:07:13.933 --> 00:07:15.477
How are you?

00:07:15.477 --> 00:07:16.811
I'd heard the story
about this battle,

00:07:16.811 --> 00:07:18.563
and reporters
were all so caught up

00:07:18.563 --> 00:07:21.608
in covering policy or
covering where were the WMDs,

00:07:21.608 --> 00:07:24.653
that we'd forgotten
that there was a war going on.

00:07:24.653 --> 00:07:26.488
It's good to see you.
SPICER: How are you?

00:07:26.488 --> 00:07:28.657
RADDATZ: No one had asked them
those questions.

00:07:28.657 --> 00:07:31.242
And I think, for them
and for their spouses,

00:07:31.242 --> 00:07:34.079
just talking about that
was healthy and helpful.

00:07:34.079 --> 00:07:37.040
WILD: There was a guy about
a hundred yards that way.

00:07:37.040 --> 00:07:41.503
That's the first guy I can
clearly remember engaging,

00:07:41.503 --> 00:07:43.213
once we were on the rooftop.

00:07:43.213 --> 00:07:45.173
ALANNE: When Mike Medavoy
first sent me the book,

00:07:45.173 --> 00:07:46.925
I just fell in love with it.

00:07:46.925 --> 00:07:49.135
It wasn't just a story
about what it's like

00:07:49.135 --> 00:07:51.054
to really go to war
for the first time,

00:07:51.054 --> 00:07:52.389
for the American soldier,

00:07:52.389 --> 00:07:54.182
but also for the American
military family.

00:07:54.182 --> 00:07:56.434
♪♪

00:07:56.434 --> 00:07:57.852
BELLAMY: She loves the troops,

00:07:57.852 --> 00:08:01.022
and it's proven
in everything she does.

00:08:01.022 --> 00:08:04.109
RADDATZ: I felt like this
civilian bridge to the military.

00:08:04.109 --> 00:08:06.152
I could talk to the spouses

00:08:06.152 --> 00:08:09.072
in ways that their husbands
sometimes didn't talk to them.

00:08:09.072 --> 00:08:11.908
ALANNE: I feel like she rescued
all these soldiers,

00:08:11.908 --> 00:08:13.785
all these families,
from being lost to history,

00:08:13.785 --> 00:08:16.746
and that that is the work that
we are carrying forward here.

00:08:16.746 --> 00:08:19.916
ABRAHAM: Background!
CREW MAN: Background.

00:08:19.916 --> 00:08:23.586
RADDATZ: The soldiers in
the story are the everyday guys.

00:08:23.586 --> 00:08:24.879
SMITH: You stay safe
out there, Tomas.

00:08:24.879 --> 00:08:26.506
TOMAS: I will.

00:08:26.506 --> 00:08:30.176
RADDATZ: They're as close to you
and me as anybody can be.

00:08:30.176 --> 00:08:33.430
Most of them never imagined
they would be in combat.

00:08:33.430 --> 00:08:36.433
ALANNE: None of them had ever
fired a weapon at an enemy

00:08:36.433 --> 00:08:38.268
or had been fired on
by the enemy.

00:08:38.268 --> 00:08:40.520
I think that just made
the heroism and bravery

00:08:40.520 --> 00:08:43.314
of that day
all the more extraordinary.

00:08:43.314 --> 00:08:47.152
The scope of the story
is really enormous.

00:08:47.152 --> 00:08:49.612
The structure that I proposed
was very ambitious,

00:08:49.612 --> 00:08:52.157
where we would have
eight main characters

00:08:52.157 --> 00:08:53.616
who we follow through
the entire event,

00:08:53.616 --> 00:08:55.368
almost in real time.

00:08:55.368 --> 00:08:58.455
And each hour would mark one
of the big defining moments

00:08:58.455 --> 00:09:00.832
in this battle.

00:09:00.832 --> 00:09:03.001
It represented this fascinating
puzzle to put together.

00:09:03.001 --> 00:09:04.711
Well, who do you choose?

00:09:04.711 --> 00:09:06.713
What hour belongs
to which character?

00:09:06.713 --> 00:09:09.674
♪♪

00:09:09.674 --> 00:09:13.052
We are very honored
to be doing this project

00:09:13.052 --> 00:09:15.805
with the support and assistance
of the United States Army

00:09:15.805 --> 00:09:17.307
and Department of Defense,

00:09:17.307 --> 00:09:19.559
who have been
such amazing partners to us

00:09:19.559 --> 00:09:21.311
from the beginning.

00:09:21.311 --> 00:09:24.189
HOMAYOUN: Mikko's dedication
to this project is infinite.

00:09:24.189 --> 00:09:27.108
QUINLAN: He has taken years
to reach out the families,

00:09:27.108 --> 00:09:30.653
the soldiers,
to get every detail right.

00:09:30.653 --> 00:09:34.032
SMITH: We kept in contact
through e-mails,

00:09:34.032 --> 00:09:36.659
and he's constantly
sending me pictures.

00:09:36.659 --> 00:09:39.537
He has been wonderful
through the whole thing.

00:09:39.537 --> 00:09:41.498
ALANNE: I just wanted to
introduce you to Robert.

00:09:41.498 --> 00:09:43.208
SMITH: Oh. (chuckles)

00:09:43.208 --> 00:09:45.919
ALANNE: Robert?
ROBERT: Oh.

00:09:48.379 --> 00:09:49.839
ROBERT: Excuse me.

00:09:49.839 --> 00:09:53.343
♪♪

00:09:53.343 --> 00:09:54.886
SMITH: It's almost like closure.

00:09:54.886 --> 00:09:56.095
It's a different
kind of closure.

00:09:56.095 --> 00:09:57.931
That was his gift to us.

00:10:04.187 --> 00:10:07.440
RADDATZ: He loves these guys.
He loves them like I do.

00:10:07.440 --> 00:10:10.485
He loves these families.
He knows them like I do.

00:10:10.485 --> 00:10:13.071
SALOMON: Let's go, one.
ABRAHAM: So, guys,

00:10:13.071 --> 00:10:16.741
let the sporadic shooting
be really sporadic.

00:10:16.741 --> 00:10:18.618
HOMAYOUN: The two directors
that we're working with

00:10:18.618 --> 00:10:21.037
are Phil Abraham
and Mikael Salomon.

00:10:21.037 --> 00:10:22.872
ABRAHAM: And action!

00:10:22.872 --> 00:10:25.917
ANDERSON: One of the things
that we knew about Phil Abraham

00:10:25.917 --> 00:10:28.419
from the work on "Mad Men"
and "The Sopranos"

00:10:28.419 --> 00:10:30.630
is that he was
very much interested

00:10:30.630 --> 00:10:34.551
in the journey of the character,
and was able to focus on that

00:10:34.551 --> 00:10:37.053
as being a guiding
storytelling principle.

00:10:37.053 --> 00:10:38.471
AGUERO:
I'm almost nearing black.

00:10:38.471 --> 00:10:40.348
I'm not sure how long
we have now. Over.

00:10:40.348 --> 00:10:43.935
VOLESKY: We're coming, Red One.
We're gonna get you out. Over.

00:10:43.935 --> 00:10:46.187
ALANNE: I wanted someone who
would really get to the heart

00:10:46.187 --> 00:10:47.647
of who these characters were,

00:10:47.647 --> 00:10:50.191
and Phil has done
a remarkable job with that.

00:10:50.191 --> 00:10:51.609
CREW MAN:
(speaking indistinctly)

00:10:51.609 --> 00:10:53.027
ABRAHAM: Yeah, that's great.
Here we go.

00:10:53.027 --> 00:10:55.530
CREW MAN: Action, vehicles.
(explosion)

00:10:55.530 --> 00:10:57.699
ALANNE: Mikael
did "Band of Brothers,"

00:10:57.699 --> 00:10:59.576
and it's been wonderful
being able to entrust him

00:10:59.576 --> 00:11:01.995
to realizing all these battles

00:11:01.995 --> 00:11:04.247
in ways that feel new
every time.

00:11:04.247 --> 00:11:06.875
♪♪

00:11:06.875 --> 00:11:08.418
ANDERSON: We realized

00:11:08.418 --> 00:11:11.421
the marrying of
the two types of storytellers

00:11:11.421 --> 00:11:13.798
was going to give us
an emotional journey

00:11:13.798 --> 00:11:16.718
that was a character journey,
but also could bring us

00:11:16.718 --> 00:11:18.803
into what the experience
of war was like.

00:11:18.803 --> 00:11:20.847
(machine-gun fire)

00:11:20.847 --> 00:11:23.141
VOLESKY: At all times, be aware.

00:11:23.141 --> 00:11:26.185
This is a skilled
and highly prepared enemy

00:11:26.185 --> 00:11:28.688
who has coordinated
a citywide attack.

00:11:28.688 --> 00:11:34.402
♪♪

00:11:34.402 --> 00:11:36.529
RADDATZ: What struck me
about this story was

00:11:36.529 --> 00:11:40.617
that these wives back home
had no idea that their husbands

00:11:40.617 --> 00:11:43.912
were in the middle of
a terrible, terrible battle.

00:11:43.912 --> 00:11:45.622
Their lives were just going on

00:11:45.622 --> 00:11:47.916
until that moment
when they knew,

00:11:47.916 --> 00:11:49.542
and their lives changed.

00:11:49.542 --> 00:11:51.336
LeAnn: A platoon
has been attacked.

00:11:51.336 --> 00:11:53.880
RITTER: The wives all
rely on each other.

00:11:53.880 --> 00:11:55.882
LUPITA: Please
get them home to us.

00:11:55.882 --> 00:11:57.592
RITTER: And they also turn
to the Readiness Group,

00:11:57.592 --> 00:12:01.471
which helps them cope
with the very specific stresses

00:12:01.471 --> 00:12:03.014
that having a husband
deployed create.

00:12:03.014 --> 00:12:05.141
LeAnn: Always remember
that you're not alone.

00:12:05.141 --> 00:12:07.435
Family Readiness is family.

00:12:07.435 --> 00:12:09.604
CALLIES: Having served
in the Army gives LeAnn Volesky

00:12:09.604 --> 00:12:11.606
a perspective that a lot of
the other wives don't.

00:12:11.606 --> 00:12:13.858
She knows what it's like
to stand in shoes

00:12:13.858 --> 00:12:15.610
like her husband's.

00:12:15.610 --> 00:12:17.362
LeAnn: The Lord never gives us
more than we can handle.

00:12:17.362 --> 00:12:19.364
GINA: I wish I had your faith.

00:12:19.364 --> 00:12:21.783
BOSWORTH: Self-doubt is
something that we all face.

00:12:21.783 --> 00:12:24.869
Gina Denomy had multiple facets
relating to that.

00:12:24.869 --> 00:12:27.330
One of them was being a new mom,
but then also participating

00:12:27.330 --> 00:12:29.582
in the care groups
the way that she did.

00:12:29.582 --> 00:12:31.209
That was very new for her.

00:12:31.209 --> 00:12:34.003
Gina had to learn to become
a leader in that way.

00:12:34.003 --> 00:12:37.256
GINA: I promise,
as soon as we're able,

00:12:37.256 --> 00:12:41.010
we will contact you,
and, hopefully, with good news.

00:12:41.010 --> 00:12:42.428
BOSWORTH: So, she's an
extraordinary woman.

00:12:42.428 --> 00:12:45.807
I feel very, very honored
to play her.

00:12:45.807 --> 00:12:47.225
RADDATZ: Look at you,
holding hands.

00:12:47.225 --> 00:12:49.394
So Shane, how --
AMBER: We've been married

00:12:49.394 --> 00:12:51.062
almost 19 years, so, yeah.
RADDATZ: Shane, how...

00:12:51.062 --> 00:12:53.439
PAXTON: Playing a real person
who went through this,

00:12:53.439 --> 00:12:57.318
it's an extreme responsibility
and it's not one I take lightly.

00:12:57.318 --> 00:13:00.488
The best I can do
is honor her story

00:13:00.488 --> 00:13:03.741
and play the situations
that have been written

00:13:03.741 --> 00:13:06.786
as truthfully as possible.
AMBER: I love you.

00:13:06.786 --> 00:13:08.413
ALANNE: Alpha Company
in this story

00:13:08.413 --> 00:13:11.165
was mostly African-American
and Hispanic soldiers.

00:13:11.165 --> 00:13:12.875
I wanted to make sure
that the diversity

00:13:12.875 --> 00:13:15.503
of our armed forces
was accurately represented.

00:13:15.503 --> 00:13:17.088
BUTLER: Hang in there, Cason.

00:13:17.088 --> 00:13:19.507
ALANNE: We looked at
who had interesting stories

00:13:19.507 --> 00:13:21.426
that could speak
to the unit as a whole.

00:13:21.426 --> 00:13:23.219
ARSIAGA: I got
a bad feeling, man.

00:13:23.219 --> 00:13:25.930
GARZA: Just stay close.
You'll be all right, man.

00:13:25.930 --> 00:13:27.682
ALANNE: And I just thought
there was something so beautiful

00:13:27.682 --> 00:13:30.560
about the friendship between
Robert Arsiaga and Israel Garza,

00:13:30.560 --> 00:13:32.562
who are just
these ordinary guys.

00:13:32.562 --> 00:13:34.981
GARZA: I never had a brother
before you.

00:13:34.981 --> 00:13:36.399
RADDATZ: I was surprised

00:13:36.399 --> 00:13:37.942
how close they came
to those characters.

00:13:37.942 --> 00:13:41.195
They really did capture
who those people are.

00:13:41.195 --> 00:13:42.655
CREW MAN: Michael?
VOLESKY: Hi.

00:13:42.655 --> 00:13:44.198
KELLY: General, how are you?
VOLESKY: Hey.

00:13:44.198 --> 00:13:45.783
It's great to see you.
How are you?

00:13:45.783 --> 00:13:47.076
KELLY: What a pleasure.

00:13:47.076 --> 00:13:48.536
VOLESKY: No,
the pleasure is mine!

00:13:48.536 --> 00:13:49.996
CLARK: Michael Kelly is
a brilliant actor.

00:13:49.996 --> 00:13:51.456
and he plays
Lieutenant Gary Volesky,

00:13:51.456 --> 00:13:53.291
our commander in the field.

00:13:53.291 --> 00:13:56.252
KELLY: I met General Volesky.

00:13:56.252 --> 00:13:58.755
(chuckling) It was, I mean,

00:13:58.755 --> 00:14:01.007
probably one of the coolest
moments I've had in my life.

00:14:11.059 --> 00:14:13.770
KELLY: I understood fully,
for the first time,

00:14:13.770 --> 00:14:15.229
how every one of his men
that I've talked to

00:14:15.229 --> 00:14:16.522
said they'd follow him
into hell.

00:14:16.522 --> 00:14:19.317
I got it.
QUINLAN: I'm Robert Arsiaga.

00:14:19.317 --> 00:14:20.985
VOLESKY: How are you?
DIAZ: Jorge Diaz.

00:14:20.985 --> 00:14:22.445
I'm playing Garza.

00:14:27.325 --> 00:14:30.411
ALANNE: Volesky, he had such a
love and warmth toward his men.

00:14:30.411 --> 00:14:31.871
CREW MAN: Jeremy Sisto.
SISTO: It's an honor, sir.

00:14:35.958 --> 00:14:37.794
SISTO: Thank you.
VOLESKY: Okay.

00:14:37.794 --> 00:14:39.420
ALANNE: And so I wanted
to find an actor

00:14:39.420 --> 00:14:41.964
who could embody flawlessly
those two qualities.

00:14:41.964 --> 00:14:44.092
And Michael is
just extraordinary.

00:14:44.092 --> 00:14:46.344
VOLESKY: Private Randazzo.

00:14:46.344 --> 00:14:48.638
That Crusader loader
who was killed?

00:14:48.638 --> 00:14:51.057
You find out his first name
and where he was from.

00:14:51.057 --> 00:14:52.767
RANDAZZO: Yes, sir.

00:14:52.767 --> 00:14:54.560
KELLY: I wanted to do
the best job I could do,

00:14:54.560 --> 00:14:57.230
because it's a man
that I now idolize in life.

00:14:57.230 --> 00:14:58.856
AGUERO: You guys want to make it
back to base

00:14:58.856 --> 00:15:01.651
without any more
casualties, huh?

00:15:01.651 --> 00:15:03.111
Then we have to work together.

00:15:03.111 --> 00:15:05.363
CLARK: E.J. Bonilla plays
Lieutenant Shane Aguero,

00:15:05.363 --> 00:15:08.199
who showed uncommon valor
in leading his guys.

00:15:08.199 --> 00:15:11.661
And even when all hope was lost,
he kept hope alive.

00:15:11.661 --> 00:15:13.037
AGUERO: The number of places

00:15:13.037 --> 00:15:14.914
that building
can come under fire from,

00:15:14.914 --> 00:15:17.542
in retrospect,
is a lot more than this can.

00:15:17.542 --> 00:15:19.877
The problem was,
it's also a lot harder

00:15:19.877 --> 00:15:21.921
to get here
for them to find us.

00:15:21.921 --> 00:15:24.632
BONILLA: He is
an unassuming hero.

00:15:24.632 --> 00:15:27.093
But when it comes to it,
he's the guy

00:15:27.093 --> 00:15:30.096
you want by your side
when you're at war.

00:15:30.096 --> 00:15:33.558
DENOMY: We will never forget
our brothers

00:15:33.558 --> 00:15:36.727
and what they did for us,

00:15:36.727 --> 00:15:39.188
and there will be time
to grieve.

00:15:39.188 --> 00:15:40.898
CLARK: Jason Ritter
plays Captain Denomy

00:15:40.898 --> 00:15:42.984
as this incredible character

00:15:42.984 --> 00:15:44.527
who, despite being wounded
multiple times,

00:15:44.527 --> 00:15:46.654
went back out in the field
to rescue these guys

00:15:46.654 --> 00:15:49.490
and led his troops
into the eye of the storm.

00:15:49.490 --> 00:15:52.285
(machine-gun fire, explosion)

00:15:52.285 --> 00:15:54.871
SISTO: Yo, there he is.
Hey!

00:15:54.871 --> 00:15:56.414
How are you?

00:15:56.414 --> 00:15:58.040
ROBERT: Pretty good,
pretty good.

00:15:58.040 --> 00:15:59.584
ALANNE: Robert Miltenberger,
to me, is one of the most

00:15:59.584 --> 00:16:01.252
fascinating characters
in this story.

00:16:01.252 --> 00:16:03.379
He's deeply embittered
by the fact

00:16:03.379 --> 00:16:06.007
that he's been stop-loss,
and on top of that,

00:16:06.007 --> 00:16:07.842
then has the certainty
that he's going to die.

00:16:07.842 --> 00:16:09.844
SISTO: It's pretty impressive,

00:16:09.844 --> 00:16:11.971
the fact that you were able
to carry out in that.

00:16:11.971 --> 00:16:15.474
And the calm in the midst
of all that, was, uh...

00:16:15.474 --> 00:16:17.685
ROBERT: I probably
surprised, me, too.

00:16:17.685 --> 00:16:20.146
I was never scared.
SISTO: I know.

00:16:20.146 --> 00:16:21.731
That's what it sounded like.
ROBERT: (laughs)

00:16:21.731 --> 00:16:23.691
ROBERT: I was never scared.

00:16:23.691 --> 00:16:26.444
I guess I was ready.
SISTO: Yeah?

00:16:26.444 --> 00:16:29.405
ROBERT: If it was my time,
I was ready.

00:16:29.405 --> 00:16:30.698
SISTO: Robert actually is,
in some ways,

00:16:30.698 --> 00:16:32.575
healthier than
some other soldiers

00:16:32.575 --> 00:16:34.702
that weren't consciously
aware of the sadness,

00:16:34.702 --> 00:16:36.787
the tragedy of it all.

00:16:36.787 --> 00:16:40.249
ROBERT: There's no glory
out there, no heroes.

00:16:40.249 --> 00:16:42.877
It's just death.

00:16:42.877 --> 00:16:44.754
(indistinct shouting)

00:16:44.754 --> 00:16:46.797
AL-LANI: (speaking Arabic)

00:16:50.051 --> 00:16:52.595
HOMAYOUN: I'm playing
Jassim Al-Lani.

00:16:52.595 --> 00:16:55.473
I'm the midpoint between
the Iraqis and the Americans.

00:16:55.473 --> 00:16:58.726
ESSAM: (speaking Arabic)

00:16:58.726 --> 00:17:00.853
HOMAYOUN: I am constantly having

00:17:00.853 --> 00:17:03.189
to choose
where my allegiances lie.

00:17:03.189 --> 00:17:04.440
AGUERO: Jassim?
BOURQUIN: Sir?

00:17:04.440 --> 00:17:05.858
AGUERO: Take it.

00:17:05.858 --> 00:17:07.777
BOURQUIN: Sir, you cannot
give him a weapon.

00:17:07.777 --> 00:17:09.445
HOMAYOUN: Some of the soldiers
distrust my character

00:17:09.445 --> 00:17:11.447
because their lives are at stake
and they don't know me.

00:17:11.447 --> 00:17:13.950
BOURQUIN: This was
a well-planned ambush.

00:17:13.950 --> 00:17:16.577
Somebody tipped the enemy off
to our movements.

00:17:16.577 --> 00:17:18.537
BEAVERS: I'm playing
Sergeant Eric Bourquin.

00:17:18.537 --> 00:17:20.081
He's a squad leader.

00:17:20.081 --> 00:17:23.876
He kind of represents
the violence of action.

00:17:23.876 --> 00:17:26.337
He's the bulldozer, a guy
you don't want to mess with.

00:17:26.337 --> 00:17:28.464
WILD: We're all gonna die.

00:17:28.464 --> 00:17:30.007
(machine-gun fire)

00:17:30.007 --> 00:17:31.884
BOURQUIN: Crying doesn't help.

00:17:31.884 --> 00:17:34.178
♪♪

00:17:34.178 --> 00:17:37.807
CLARK: Our first choices said
yes on this show for the cast,

00:17:37.807 --> 00:17:40.434
and nowhere
was that more important

00:17:40.434 --> 00:17:42.061
than in the home front.

00:17:42.061 --> 00:17:43.312
ABRAHAM: And action!

00:17:43.312 --> 00:17:44.939
The way we shot the show,

00:17:44.939 --> 00:17:47.567
we did all the home-front work
up front.

00:17:47.567 --> 00:17:51.529
So, literally, 9, 10 days
after shooting began,

00:17:51.529 --> 00:17:53.781
we never saw
our ladies again, ever.

00:17:53.781 --> 00:17:57.702
GINA: You know, before he left,
Troy said, in ancient times,

00:17:57.702 --> 00:17:59.704
wives went to war
with their husbands.

00:17:59.704 --> 00:18:03.791
I guess we still do that,
in a way.

00:18:03.791 --> 00:18:06.377
BOSWORTH: Everyone
who's been a part of this

00:18:06.377 --> 00:18:09.255
has taken it on
like a personal mission

00:18:09.255 --> 00:18:11.215
to shine a light on this event,

00:18:11.215 --> 00:18:15.344
and to honor it
in the best way that we can.

00:18:15.344 --> 00:18:17.138
(camera shutter clicking)

00:18:17.138 --> 00:18:19.682
PHOTOGRAPHER: You two together,
that's good.

00:18:19.682 --> 00:18:22.059
BEAVERS: We would bleed
to do right by them.

00:18:22.059 --> 00:18:23.686
PHOTOGRAPHER: Cool.
BEAVERS: And to get to meet

00:18:23.686 --> 00:18:25.980
the real heroes
that we're portraying

00:18:25.980 --> 00:18:27.732
and have them bring us in
for a hug

00:18:27.732 --> 00:18:30.693
and say, "Hey man, we think
you're gonna do a great job.

00:18:30.693 --> 00:18:33.321
We trust you,
and you have our blessing,"

00:18:33.321 --> 00:18:36.157
I feel so much responsibility,
and I also feel

00:18:36.157 --> 00:18:38.868
so much privilege.
KELLY: Michael.

00:18:38.868 --> 00:18:39.952
What's your name?
JOHN: John.

00:18:39.952 --> 00:18:41.787
KELLY: John.
I owe it to them

00:18:41.787 --> 00:18:44.832
to do this the best that I can,
because the country should know.

00:18:44.832 --> 00:18:47.335
QUINLAN: We've been incredibly
fortunate on this project

00:18:47.335 --> 00:18:49.253
to actually meet
and be counseled by

00:18:49.253 --> 00:18:51.172
the soldiers who were
part of this battle.

00:18:51.172 --> 00:18:54.300
ALANNE: We wanted our actors
to go through a boot camp

00:18:54.300 --> 00:18:56.594
not only to learn
to move properly

00:18:56.594 --> 00:18:58.596
and act properly as soldiers,
but also for

00:18:58.596 --> 00:19:00.431
the bonding experience
that that would provide.

00:19:00.431 --> 00:19:03.142
BAUMGARTEN: We put together
a weeklong boot camp

00:19:03.142 --> 00:19:05.811
that not only incorporated
the basic infantry skills --

00:19:05.811 --> 00:19:07.772
weapons handling, tactics,
things like that --

00:19:07.772 --> 00:19:09.732
but also to understand
the weight and the gravity

00:19:09.732 --> 00:19:11.233
of what the actors
were representing.

00:19:22.286 --> 00:19:24.497
ALANNE: Mike Baumgarten
and Jerry Goodenmen,

00:19:24.497 --> 00:19:27.166
who were our chief
technical advisers,

00:19:27.166 --> 00:19:29.627
led the boot camp
with two real-life veterans

00:19:29.627 --> 00:19:32.213
of this battle,
Eric Bourquin and Aaron Fowler.

00:19:32.213 --> 00:19:34.882
BAUMGARTEN: Let's go.
HOMAYOUN: We would run drills

00:19:34.882 --> 00:19:37.093
of clearing houses,
patrolling streets...

00:19:37.093 --> 00:19:39.053
(machine-gun fire)

00:19:39.053 --> 00:19:41.430
...and fail over and over.

00:19:52.692 --> 00:19:56.529
BEAVERS: They don't compromise,
so we recognize pretty quickly

00:19:56.529 --> 00:19:59.407
that we're gonna
get it right, period.

00:19:59.407 --> 00:20:00.783
We're gonna go the route
that we went,

00:20:00.783 --> 00:20:02.284
entering the building last time,

00:20:02.284 --> 00:20:03.869
and we're just gonna,
instead, we're gonna peel

00:20:03.869 --> 00:20:05.287
and get to the edge
of that building,

00:20:05.287 --> 00:20:07.081
peel into the staircase
like that.

00:20:07.081 --> 00:20:08.499
Does that make sense?
CREW MAN: Let's do it.

00:20:08.499 --> 00:20:10.126
KELLY: Slow and steady.
Communicate.

00:20:10.126 --> 00:20:13.546
BOURQUIN: The actors were asking
about the proper way

00:20:13.546 --> 00:20:15.840
to hold the weapons, how to
shoot, move, and communicate.

00:20:15.840 --> 00:20:17.341
AGUERO: I approve
of this training.

00:20:17.341 --> 00:20:19.051
He has finger where
it's supposed to be at.

00:20:19.051 --> 00:20:20.845
BOURQUIN: Look how well
all these guys are patrolling.

00:20:20.845 --> 00:20:23.389
They're watching the corners,
and they're checking doors.

00:20:23.389 --> 00:20:25.182
They're passing it off.
AGUERO: Yeah.

00:20:25.182 --> 00:20:28.185
It looks good. It looks good.
BAUMGARTEN: All the actors,

00:20:28.185 --> 00:20:30.563
you want to get
as much correct as possible.

00:20:30.563 --> 00:20:33.232
They could easily remove us
from the process

00:20:33.232 --> 00:20:34.775
and just do what they want,
but they didn't.

00:20:34.775 --> 00:20:36.068
They care about the story.

00:20:36.068 --> 00:20:39.196
CREW MAN: Fire. Hold.
Fire. Hold.

00:20:39.196 --> 00:20:40.906
DENMAN: We were holding them
to a standard,

00:20:40.906 --> 00:20:42.783
making them do 20 good reps

00:20:42.783 --> 00:20:44.493
before we were good
for them to move on...

00:20:44.493 --> 00:20:47.455
QUINLAN: Cut! Ooh, I think
that was a tie, no?

00:20:47.455 --> 00:20:49.123
-DENMAN: ...just so that,
when they get out here

00:20:49.123 --> 00:20:50.624
and there's cameras
in their face,

00:20:50.624 --> 00:20:52.626
and they're tired,
they'll remember.

00:20:52.626 --> 00:20:54.545
BEAVERS: My team, let's all
do a buddy system.

00:20:54.545 --> 00:20:57.339
Take your mag out,
pull your bolt back,

00:20:57.339 --> 00:20:59.633
take a look
if there's no brass, yeah?

00:20:59.633 --> 00:21:01.510
RITTER: It was kind of amazing
because, at a certain point,

00:21:01.510 --> 00:21:03.721
we could notice what
each other were doing

00:21:03.721 --> 00:21:05.639
and sort of police
each other a little bit

00:21:05.639 --> 00:21:08.142
and say, "Get your elbow down,"
or "You got to keep your barrel

00:21:08.142 --> 00:21:10.603
not aimed
at your fellow soldier."

00:21:10.603 --> 00:21:12.229
BEAVERS: All right.
Here we go, closing doors.

00:21:12.229 --> 00:21:13.981
On me. You ready?
QUINLAN: Yeah, ready!

00:21:13.981 --> 00:21:16.108
Come on back.

