BEAVERS: We were thrown
into scenarios

00:21:17.610 --> 00:21:19.403
that none of us felt
comfortable with.

00:21:19.403 --> 00:21:21.071
Right there!

00:21:21.071 --> 00:21:22.490
But, you know, Mike and Jericho
who kept telling us,

00:21:22.490 --> 00:21:24.116
"Just do your best."
Let's go.

00:21:24.116 --> 00:21:25.451
QUINLAN: Mike kept saying,

00:21:25.451 --> 00:21:27.411
"You're given
principles to live by,

00:21:27.411 --> 00:21:30.414
and you must make the best of
a bad situation at all times."

00:21:30.414 --> 00:21:32.333
We all got each other's backs.

00:21:32.333 --> 00:21:35.419
KELLY: All you want to do is
get their praise,

00:21:35.419 --> 00:21:37.713
because these are guys
who really lived it.

00:21:37.713 --> 00:21:39.089
Go!

00:21:39.089 --> 00:21:41.800
♪♪

00:21:41.800 --> 00:21:44.762
So we all really
busted our ass to do it.

00:21:44.762 --> 00:21:47.139
SISTO: For me,
this is the first time

00:21:47.139 --> 00:21:49.016
where I kind of
really felt like --

00:21:49.016 --> 00:21:52.228
like we were really
like brothers and...

00:21:52.228 --> 00:21:53.938
KELLY: Yeah. Yeah.
SISTO: And as an actor,

00:21:53.938 --> 00:21:55.689
that's what I'm looking for,
about this thing.

00:21:55.689 --> 00:21:57.191
So thank you for
making that all happen.

00:21:57.191 --> 00:21:58.901
KELLY: Thank you, Mike.
SISTO: Thanks, Mike.

00:21:58.901 --> 00:22:02.488
(cheers and applause)

00:22:08.494 --> 00:22:10.829
QUINLAN: Oh, this is so rad!

00:22:10.829 --> 00:22:13.374
FISHER: The boot camp really did
bring everybody together

00:22:13.374 --> 00:22:15.000
in a really wonderful way.

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:17.127
The bond on this set
is something special.

00:22:17.127 --> 00:22:21.924
ALANNE: It's been amazing
having the Army as our adviser,

00:22:21.924 --> 00:22:25.219
because I always wanted this
to be as authentic as possible.

00:22:25.219 --> 00:22:27.555
I want to thank everyone
here in Fort Hood.

00:22:27.555 --> 00:22:30.724
We have been welcomed here
with such love and care.

00:22:30.724 --> 00:22:32.184
It's been amazing,

00:22:32.184 --> 00:22:34.436
and we are eternally grateful
for that.

00:22:34.436 --> 00:22:37.690
RIDDELL: So, Wild,
if we don't make it back,

00:22:37.690 --> 00:22:39.358
who do you think

00:22:39.358 --> 00:22:41.110
should play us
in the movie version?

00:22:41.110 --> 00:22:44.363
WILD: Think I'd like Tom Cruise.
RIDDELL: Nah, he's too tall.

00:22:44.363 --> 00:22:45.864
WILD: Screw you, man.

00:22:45.864 --> 00:22:48.075
♪♪

00:22:48.075 --> 00:22:50.244
SALOMON: Thank you, everybody.
Positions, please.

00:22:50.244 --> 00:22:52.204
ALANNE: We were gonna
get this story told,

00:22:52.204 --> 00:22:53.664
no matter how long it took.

00:22:53.664 --> 00:22:56.542
We initially developed it
as a three-hour feature.

00:22:56.542 --> 00:22:59.211
SALOMON: Here we go!
ALANNE: It's been

00:22:59.211 --> 00:23:00.796
so extraordinary now
to be able to bring

00:23:00.796 --> 00:23:03.882
an even more fully realized
version of this,

00:23:03.882 --> 00:23:05.175
expanding it to eight hours,

00:23:05.175 --> 00:23:06.677
together with
National Geographic.

00:23:06.677 --> 00:23:09.179
♪♪

00:23:09.179 --> 00:23:10.556
ANDERSON: These were the guys

00:23:10.556 --> 00:23:13.142
that we wanted to
take this journey with.

00:23:13.142 --> 00:23:15.269
They understood the importance
of the material

00:23:15.269 --> 00:23:17.896
and why we had been sticking
with it for so long.

00:23:17.896 --> 00:23:19.440
ALANNE: They have been
such amazing partners.

00:23:19.440 --> 00:23:20.983
From the very beginning,
they were attracted

00:23:20.983 --> 00:23:23.527
to the ambition and
complexity of the project.

00:23:23.527 --> 00:23:25.404
SALOMON: Action!
(machine-gun fire)

00:23:25.404 --> 00:23:28.657
BONILLA: National Geographic is
famous for telling the truth.

00:23:28.657 --> 00:23:30.492
I love that they're
making honest, real,

00:23:30.492 --> 00:23:32.328
hard-hitting television.

00:23:32.328 --> 00:23:36.624
This is the closest we can get
without being there ourselves.

00:23:36.624 --> 00:23:39.209
♪♪

00:23:39.209 --> 00:23:42.671
BOURQUIN: They ambushed us
to draw out the rescues.

00:23:42.671 --> 00:23:44.340
Now they're gonna come
for us for real.

00:23:44.340 --> 00:23:46.133
ALANNE: When you watch it,
you literally feel

00:23:46.133 --> 00:23:48.677
that you are trapped in the
situation with our characters.

00:23:48.677 --> 00:23:50.846
AGUERO: We got to move!
RADDATZ: You will feel

00:23:50.846 --> 00:23:55.059
exactly what those soldiers
and what those families felt.

00:23:55.059 --> 00:23:57.353
♪♪

00:23:57.353 --> 00:23:59.521
KELLY: The events
of April 4, 2004,

00:23:59.521 --> 00:24:01.398
happened so quickly
and instinctively

00:24:01.398 --> 00:24:04.818
that their true impact could
only be revealed in hindsight.

00:24:04.818 --> 00:24:07.696
What has emerged, looking back
all these years later,

00:24:07.696 --> 00:24:11.158
is a portrait not just
of courage and sacrifice,

00:24:11.158 --> 00:24:13.577
but one of family...
GARZA: You doing all right?

00:24:13.577 --> 00:24:15.621
KELLY: ...not just at home
and on the front lines,

00:24:15.621 --> 00:24:18.248
but now on both sides
of the camera, as well.

00:24:18.248 --> 00:24:20.501
SALOMON: Action.

00:24:20.501 --> 00:24:22.711
KELLY: It is a bond that serves
as a fitting tribute

00:24:22.711 --> 00:24:25.881
to the memory
of those who were lost.

